# Cookbook â€” intent â†’ trait / type

A pattern book for "I need to X" questions. Pick the matching intent,
use the suggested trait / type. When none fits, the correct answer is
usually "add a trait to hilavitkutin-api", not "use a std primitive".

## "I need to return an optional value"

Return `Maybe<T>` (from `notko`). `Maybe::Is(v)` / `Maybe::Isnt`.

## "I need a fallible operation"

Return `Outcome<T, E>` (from `notko`). `E` is a `repr(C)` enum.

## "I need an infallible value (hot path)"

Return `Just<T>` or plain `T`. Mark the function with
`#[optimize_for(hot)]` to get the macro rewrite (AST-level Okâ†’Just,
Errâ†’panic in internal release).

## "I need to emit errors / diagnostics from a phase"

Take `&mut impl DiagnosticSink<E>` as a parameter. Return
`Outcome<Success, Aborted>`. DO NOT return `Vec<Error>`. The sink
trait ships in `hilavitkutin-api` (pending #83); until then, author a
local trait and promote later.

## "I need to emit bytes (serialization, codegen)"

Take `&mut impl ByteEmitter` as a parameter. Return
`Outcome<Meta, EmitterFull>`. DO NOT return `Vec<u8>`.

## "I need to collect items into bounded storage"

Take `&mut impl Collector<T>` as a parameter. Implementors can be
Seq-backed, array-backed, channel-backed, etc.

## "I need to declare a WorkUnit's access set"

```rust
impl WorkUnit for MyUnit {
    type Access = (Read<Column<Input>>, Write<Column<Output>>);
    fn execute(ctx: &Self::Ctx) { ... }
}
```

## "I need a context / environment binding"

Declare via associated type: `type Ctx: HasReader<Input> +
HasWriter<Output>`. Caller provides any type that satisfies the bound.

## "I need a bit pattern"

`Mask64` for â‰¤ 64 bits, `Mask256` for â‰¤ 256. From `arvo-bitmask`. For
bit-level contracts, `arvo-bits::BitSequence`.

## "I need a type-level storage declaration"

`Seq<T, N: Cap>` for ordered, `Map<K, V, N: Cap>` for keyed. These are
`hilavitkutin-api::store` ZSTs â€” declarative, not Vec-like. Allocation
is scheduler-managed.

## "I need keyâ†’value lookup"

Take `&impl KeyValueStore<K, V>`. Internally use `Map<K, V, CAP>`
(type-level descriptor).

## "I need an interned string"

`Str` from `hilavitkutin-str`. Construct const: `str_const!("foo")`.
Runtime-intern via `StringInterner`.

## "I need a FIFO cache"

`hilavitkutin-persistence::Sieve<K, V, CAP>`.

## "I need to iterate a bounded source"

`impl IntoIterator<Item = T>` or `&[T]`.

## "I need a measurement / capacity / index"

`USize` (not raw `usize`). `Cap` for const-generic capacity.

## "I need threading"

Take `&impl ThreadPoolApi`. Engine provides the implementation; never
call `thread::spawn`, `tokio::spawn`, `async_std::spawn` yourself.

## "I need memory"

Take `&mut impl MemoryProviderApi`. Never `Box::new`, `Vec::new`,
`alloc::alloc`. The engine's memory layout is planned, not fabricated.

## "I need time"

Take `&impl ClockApi`. Never `std::time::Instant::now()`.

## "I genuinely need std"

Hilavitkutin is `#![no_std]`, no alloc, no dynamic dispatch â€” by
design. If you think you need std, the API shape is wrong. File a
design round. The 22 traits in `hilavitkutin-api` cover access /
context / platform / hints â€” pick one or add one.

